segment.source: The easiest method for creating a customized Start layout to apply to other Windows 10 devices is to set up the Start screen on a test computer and then export the layout.
segment.target: The easiest method for creating a customized Start layout to apply to other Windows 10 devices is to set up the Start screen on a test computer and then export the layout.

segment.source: After you export the layout, decide whether you want to apply a full Start layout or a partial Start layout.
segment.target: After you export the layout, decide whether you want to apply a full Start layout or a partial Start layout.

segment.source: When a full Start layout is applied, the users cannot pin, unpin, or uninstall apps from Start.
segment.target: When a full Start layout is applied, the users cannot pin, unpin, or uninstall apps from Start.

segment.source: Users can view and open all apps in the All Apps view, but they cannot pin any apps to Start.
segment.target: Users can view and open all apps in the All Apps view, but they cannot pin any apps to Start.

segment.source: When a partial Start layout is applied, the contents of the specified tile groups cannot be changed, but users can move those groups, and can also create and customize their own groups.
segment.target: When a partial Start layout is applied, the contents of the specified tile groups cannot be changed, but users can move those groups, and can also create and customize their own groups.

segment.source: Note Partial Start layout is only supported on Windows 10, version 1511 and later.
segment.target: Note Partial Start layout is only supported on Windows 10, version 1511 and later.

segment.source: Customize the Start screen on your test computer
segment.target: Customize the Start screen on your test computer

segment.source: To prepare a Start layout for export, you simply customize the Start layout on a test computer.
segment.target: To prepare a Start layout for export, you simply customize the Start layout on a test computer.

segment.source: To prepare a test computer
segment.target: To prepare a test computer

segment.source: Set up a test computer on which to customize the Start layout.
segment.target: Set up a test computer on which to customize the Start layout.

segment.source: Your test computer should have the operating system that is installed on the users’ computers (Windows 10 Enterprise or Windows 10 Education).
segment.target: Your test computer should have the operating system that is installed on the users’ computers (Windows 10 Enterprise or Windows 10 Education).

segment.source: Install all apps and services that the Start layout should display.
segment.target: Install all apps and services that the Start layout should display.

segment.source: Important
segment.target: Important

segment.source: Start layout can only be applied to a device using the same architecture (32-bit or 64-bit) as the device on which Start layout was created.
segment.target: Start layout can only be applied to a device using the same architecture (32-bit or 64-bit) as the device on which Start layout was created.

segment.source: Create a new user account that you will use to customize the Start layout.
segment.target: Create a new user account that you will use to customize the Start layout.

segment.target: Sign in to your test computer with the user account that you created.

segment.target: Customize the Start layout as you want users to see it by using the following techniques:

segment.source: Pin apps to Start.
segment.target: Pin apps to Start.

segment.source: From Start, type the name of the app.
segment.target: From Start, type the name of the app.

segment.source: When the app appears in the search results, right-click the app, and then click Pin to Start.
segment.target: When the app appears in the search results, right-click the app, and then click Pin to Start.

segment.source: To view all apps, click All apps in the bottom-left corner of Start.
segment.target: To view all apps, click All apps in the bottom-left corner of Start.

segment.source: Right-click any app, and pin or unpin it from Start.
segment.target: Right-click any app, and pin or unpin it from Start.

segment.source: Unpin apps that you don’t want to display.
segment.target: Unpin apps that you don’t want to display.

segment.source: To unpin an app, right-click the app, and then click Unpin from Start.
segment.target: To unpin an app, right-click the app, and then click Unpin from Start.

segment.target: Export the Start layout

segment.source: When you have the Start layout that you want your users to see, use the Export-StartLayout cmdlet in Windows PowerShell to export the Start layout to an .xml file.
segment.target: When you have the Start layout that you want your users to see, use the Export-StartLayout cmdlet in Windows PowerShell to export the Start layout to an .xml file.

segment.target: To export the Start layout to an .xml file

segment.source: Configure a partial Start layout
segment.target: Configure a partial Start layout

segment.source: A partial Start layout enables you to add one or more customized tile groups to users' Start screens or menus, while still allowing users to make changes to other parts of the Start layout.
segment.target: A partial Start layout enables you to add one or more customized tile groups to users' Start screens or menus, while still allowing users to make changes to other parts of the Start layout.

segment.source: All groups that you add are locked, meaning users cannot change the contents of those tile groups, however users can change the location of those groups.
segment.target: All groups that you add are locked, meaning users cannot change the contents of those tile groups, however users can change the location of those groups.

segment.source: Locked groups are identified with an icon, as shown in the following image.
segment.target: Locked groups are identified with an icon, as shown in the following image.

segment.source: locked tile group
segment.target: locked tile group

segment.source: When a partial Start layout is applied for the first time, the new groups are added to the users' existing Start layouts.
segment.target: When a partial Start layout is applied for the first time, the new groups are added to the users' existing Start layouts.

segment.source: If an app tile is in both an existing group and in a new locked group, the duplicate app tile is removed from the existing (unlocked) group.
segment.target: If an app tile is in both an existing group and in a new locked group, the duplicate app tile is removed from the existing (unlocked) group.

segment.source: When a partial Start layout is applied to a device that already has a StartLayout.xml applied, groups that were added previously are removed and the groups in the new layout are added.
segment.target: When a partial Start layout is applied to a device that already has a StartLayout.xml applied, groups that were added previously are removed and the groups in the new layout are added.

segment.source: If the Start layout is applied by Group Policy or MDM, and the policy is removed, the groups remain on the devices but become unlocked.
segment.target: If the Start layout is applied by Group Policy or MDM, and the policy is removed, the groups remain on the devices but become unlocked.
